{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524453"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583822"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13996"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.01,0.11,0.07,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58557"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6630"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43959"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"},{"type":"tags","id":"1692"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"6096"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58557"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following an injury with broken glass one hour ago. He has sustained a deep laceration to the volar aspect of his left forearm, approximately 5 cm proximal to the wrist (Image). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is active bleeding from the wound. He is unable to oppose his thumb to his little finger, and has reduced sensation over the palmar aspect of his thumb, index, and middle fingers. The rest of his hand examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Digital nerve","Axillary nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Median nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of median nerve injury at the forearm level, including inability to oppose the thumb (due to paralysis of the thenar muscles) and sensory loss in the characteristic median nerve distribution. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies most of the thenar muscles via its recurrent branch, including the opponens pollicis, which is crucial for thumb opposition. It also provides sensory innervation to the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, and middle fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edigital nerves\u003C/strong\u003E are terminal branches of the median and ulnar nerves in the hand. Injury to a single digital nerve would only affect sensation to part of one digit, not cause motor deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the deltoid muscle and provides sensation to a small area over the lateral shoulder. It is not involved in hand function and would not be affected by a forearm laceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E in the forearm primarily supplies wrist and finger extensors. Injury would result in wrist drop and inability to extend the fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joints, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies most intrinsic hand muscles and sensation to the little finger and ulnar half of the ring finger. Injury would cause weakness of finger abduction/adduction and clawing of the little and ring fingers, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The median nerve innervates the thenar muscles responsible for thumb opposition.","Median nerve injury at the forearm level typically presents with weakness of thumb opposition and abduction.","The recurrent branch of the median nerve specifically supplies the thenar muscles."],"references":["Isaacs J, Ugwu-Oju O. High Median Nerve Injuries. Hand Clin 2016; 32: 339\u201348."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43959"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13996"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20890"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20890"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/M7ll2G6tsjFBdfMlrieMAey8DQ7wBR.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/M7ll2G6tsjFBdfMlrieMAey8DQ7wBR.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43959"},"attrib